The NHANES (National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey) is where it's at, at least since 1999.



http://www.cdc.gov/nchs/nhanes/nhanes_questionnaires.htm

Body measures raw data from 2009â€“2010
http://www.cdc.gov/nchs/nhanes/nhanes2009-2010/exam09_10.htm

Raw data file documentation:
http://www.cdc.gov/nchs/nhanes/nhanes2009-2010/BMX_F.htm

xport python library:
http://pypi.python.org/pypi/xport/0.1.0


Sample Python session:
import xport
reader = xport.XportReader('BMX_F.xpt')
row = reader.next()

>>> row
{'BMXTRI': 16, 'BMILEG': 0, 'BMXHEAD': 0, 'BMXLEG': 41, 'BMIWT': 0, 'BMIWAIST': 0, 'BMXBMI': 32, 'BMXRECUM': 0, 'BMIARMC': 0, 'BMIARML': 0, 'BMIHT': 0, 'BMIRECUM': 0, 'BMITRI': 0, 'BMXARML': 40, 'BMISUB': 0, 'BMIHEAD': 0, 'BMXWT': 87, 'BMXARMC': 36, 'SEQN': 51624, 'BMXWAIST': 100, 'BMXSUB': 24, 'BMXHT': 164, 'BMDSTATS': 1}

BMXBMI = Body Mass Index

From http://www.cdc.gov/nchs/nhanes/nhanes2009-2010/faqs09_10.htm#20
20. Can I identify what region of the country or what state or county a survey participant resides within?

Geographic identifiers are available but only through the Research Data Center (RDC), in order to protect the confidentiality of our participants. A list of NHANES Geocode variables is available through the RDC website.

This article is about distributions:
http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1636707/

This site has per-state data for Obese %, but not distributions so far as I can tell:
http://www.cdc.gov/obesity/data/adult.html

Gold mine! Microdata!
http://www.cdc.gov/brfss/technical_infodata/surveydata/2008.htm#sas
